text: I totally agree with you on this point. For some time I have written/said the $MSOS ETF is outsized relative to the individual company floats, making the ETF the tail that wags the cannabis dog.

Read quarterly press releases and listen to the conference calls of the leading msos- the stocks are lower because of fundamental conditions and the other factors I mentioned not Algos/arb/conspiracies … I respectfully disagree with you.

@todd_harrison The investment dynamic in cannabis is complex - all these factors are contributing factors but I weigh fundamentals as far more important. If the fundies were improving and not eroding the stocks would have been much higher in price even without custody/uplisting.

I never said that custody and uplisting issues are not limiting factors to the industry's valuations/popularity. Indeed that is why I have written that legislation is so important. But the key factor has been the eroding fundamentals, imho @Tyler_Neville
and evidence that the total addressable market was smaller than generally believed. @yongecity

To me fundamentals "trump" most price narratives or conspiracy theories (e.g. algo/machine influence) Cannabis stocks fell because of the factors I tweeted about to Todd early this morning - eroding fundies, expansion of illicit mkt, poor prospects for legislation, price pressure

Nearly all the cannabis analysts took company guidance as gospel in the last two years - only to take down estimates and price targets after companies took down their guidance (ex post facto). @todd_harrison @dougkass

I would add that most if not all the cannabis sell side analysts were slow in taking down their estimates and price targets. I dont know one that was anticipatory, all or nearly all reactionary. Today's magnitude of the $TCNNF price target from over $40 to $20 is an example.

I dont know what you mean in this tweet, Toddo. Over the last two years, price targets have continually dropped (precipitously) as a direct result of weakening industry fundamentals (absolutely and relative to consensus) and fading legislative initiatives.

T lets agree to disagree. Custody and uplisting are impt big picture issues but the volatility factor trade, to me, is a side show to all the adverse fundamental factors that have developed over the last two years (which have adversely influenced the stocks). Same applies to mkt

My constant refrain on @TSTRMPro Buyers live higher (and sellers live lower) in an investment landscape dominated by machines and algos (who know little about value but everything about price). @tomkeene @lisaabramowicz1 @jimcramer

Toddo, this helps underscore my tweets to you. ATB halves its price target to $21 based on "more diff macro" and limited state rollouts. Again, a reduced TAM (total addressable market) concern with disappointing organic +. Not an "arbitrage" issue, more fundamental, respectfully.

Agree @KeithMcCullough Still have the lagged effect of recent int rates hikes and QT that will more than double in size in September at the time we experience a global recession. The Fed stopped hiking rates in January, 2001/June, 2006 - it did not work out well for equities.
Finally... The challenge of creating signature brands (like @bcobblaw is doing in Fla will "weed out" company winners from losers. Next thing to watch, imho.

Yes the elephant in the room is the custody and uplisting issues - ergo my view that Washington DC holds the key for cannabis equities. And yes, by definition, a retail centric shareholder base becomes sentiment driven but that ignores the fundamental challenges last 2 years.

answer: you don't! for a long time i have been of the view that the fate of cannabis stocks lies in washington dc. nothing has changed, particularly in light of the weakening fundamentals relative to consensus expectations.

Toddo The other problem I suspect that has plagued cannabis stocks and has been rarely discussed - is the lack of and uncertainty relative to organic growth (before we include new state/market roll outs). This has likely produced total addressable market concerns,

dulling valuations/sentiment. I like you are hopeful that this has now been discounted - it also explains why I have recently been more aggressive in my cannabis buys (as the cannons have already sounded). @threadreaderapp unroll

Respectfully disagree Msos had nothing to do with xbi and arkk - though they have all have faced a diff set of fundamental problems that have little in common save being overvalued. $arkk bought vastly overvalued non earning covid beneficiares at or near the top,

$xbi constitutency were concept biotech with little eps and $msos consisted of overvalued cannabis stocks 1-2 years ago that faced a steady deterioration in fundies (guidedowns sales/cash flow/eps) and for the reasons previously mentioned a steady flow of lower price targets

the association between $MSOS $XBI and $ARKK have some common themes but saying the narrative chases price begs the diff subset of problems that led to their respective and rapid price declines, imho. @threadreaderapp unroll

T i obv agree that custody issues and other factors have contributed to the fall in $MSOS but the dominant factors were the slow state rollouts, absence of legislation, supply/demand imbalances, deteriorating fundamentals (limited organic growth/illicit), high valuations, etc.
